news.contents: Kansas City Chiefs quarterback Patrick Mahomes looks to bounce back in Week 2 against the Jacksonville Jaguars from a subpar Week 1 performance by his lofty standards. The 27-year-old performed better than his 226-yard, two-touchdown, one-interception line would indicate after being plagued by at least six receiver drops without top target Travis Kelce (knee). Kelce will return for Sunday's contest, solidifying Mahomes as one of the weekend's premier QB1 plays. Jacksonville's defense ...
news.title: Patrick Mahomes - Week 2 Outlook for Fantasy Football

news.contents: New England Patriots running back Rhamondre Stevenson might lose some rushing opportunities to Ezekiel Elliott versus Miami on Sunday night, but he'll still be called upon for a significant role in the passing attack. Stevenson hauled in all six of his targets last week and has been the Patriots' most reliable pass-catcher at times over the last year. With the Patriots needing to pass a lot to keep up with the Dolphins, don't be surprised if Stevenson has a major role. He's a fantasy RB2 ...
news.title: Rhamondre Stevenson - Week 2 Outlook for Fantasy Football

news.contents: New York Giants running back Saquon Barkley is looking for a better offensive performance this week. The two-time Pro Bowl running back was the lone bright spot of a dreadful Week 1 for the G-Men, averaging 4.3 yards per carry against the Dallas defense. The rest of the offense had a net of 120 yards. The Cardinals' defense performed admirably against Washington in Week 1, but a less-than-stellar Arizona offense will provide Barkley and the rest of the Giants' offense more opportunities in Week...
news.title: Saquon Barkley - Week 2 Outlook for Fantasy Football

news.contents: Conner (calf) doesn't have an injury designation for Sunday's game against the Giants, Bob McManaman of The Arizona Republic reports.
news.analysis: Conner was a limited practice participant Wednesday and Thursday, before upgrading to full at the end of the week and telling reporters he felt good after the practice. He played 83 percent of Arizona's snaps on offense last week en route to 19 touches for 70 yards, while backup Keaontay Ingram was seldom-used and finished with minus-four yards on five carries. Conner should be busy again this Sunday against New York.
news.title: Cleared to play against Giants

news.contents: Smith secured four of five targets for 131 yards and a touchdown in the Eagles' 34-28 win over the Vikings on Thursday night.
news.analysis: The highlight of Smith's big night was a 63-yard touchdown reception early in the third quarter that saw the fleet-footed receiver use pure speed to get open for a perfectly-timed throw from Jalen Hurts. Smith's second catch of the game also seemed to portend a prolific night, as he logged a 54-yard grab on his second reception during Philadelphia's first drive. Smith has significantly outpaced fellow star receiver A.J. Brown through two games, as the former will take an 11-178-2 line into a Week 3 Monday night road matchup against the Buccaneers on Sept. 25.
news.title: Eclipses century mark in win

news.contents: Philadelphia Eagles wide receiver DeVonta Smith caught 4-of-5 targets for 131 yards and one touchdown during the team's 34-28 victory over the Minnesota Vikings. The former Heisman winner started the game strong with an impressive 54-yard catch over top of a defender on the team's first offensive drive. Smith capped off the night with a 63-yard touchdown where he torched the cornerback and trotted into the end zone with ease. The 24-year-old ended the 2022 season on a high note, and he has ...
news.title: DeVonta Smith Carves Up Vikings Defense For 131 Yards

news.contents: Tampa Bay Buccaneers wide receiver Chris Godwin made the most of his chances during the season opener. The 27-year-old hauled in five of his six targets for 51 yards in the win over the Minnesota Vikings. The Bucs are limited in terms of receiving weapons, so Godwin and Mike Evans are expected to be heavily utilized. For Week 2, fantasy managers should consider Godwin a solid WR2. He's heading into a matchup against the Chicago Bears who struggled against the passing attack last week. Both ...
news.title: Chris Godwin - Week 2 Outlook for Fantasy Football

news.contents: Waller (hamstring/rest) doesn't have an injury designation for Sunday's game at Arizona, Art Stapleton of The Bergen Record reports.
news.analysis: Things were trending in this direction after Waller made it through Week 1 without aggravating the hamstring and had 'rest' added to his Week 2 injury report. He caught three passes for 36 yards in the first half of a 40-0 loss to the Cowboys last week but then barely played after halftime. Waller did play 89 percent of snaps in the first half, most among New York's skill-position players, with the offense centering on him and RB Saquon Barkley until things got out of hand. A matchup with the lowly Cardinals should provide those two and the rest of the offense with better opportunities to score fantasy points, even if standout left tackle Andrew Thomas (questionable - hamstring) doesn't end up playing.
news.title: Cleared from injury report

news.contents: New York Giants tight end Darren Waller (hamstring) was limited in practice on Friday but was removed from the final injury report heading into Sunday's Week 2 matchup against the Arizona Cardinals on the road. Waller is dealing with a hamstring injury to the same leg that caused him to miss time with the Las Vegas Raiders last year, but the 31-year-old insists it's nothing remotely as serious as what he dealt with in 2022. His missed practice this week was mostly for rest purposes, and Waller ...
news.title: Darren Waller Has No Injury Status Heading Into Week 2

news.contents: Atlanta Falcons kicker Younghoe Koo converted all three extra point attempts and nailed a 49-yard field goal in Week 1 against the Carolina Panthers. Koo finished with the fifth most points among kickers last season, and will likely contend for a similar finish this year. Next, he faces the Green Bay Packers, who allowed two field goals in their own season opener against the Chicago Bears. Koo should fare well in his home dome and should be started in Week 2.
news.title: Younghoe Koo - Week 2 Outlook for Fantasy Football

news.contents: The New York Jets defense got off to a hot start against the Buffalo Bills in Week 1 and will look to slow down the Dallas Cowboys offense in Week 2. Dallas scored 27 of its 40 total points on offense last week, but Sunday's contest has a projected point total of just 38.5. With New York proving to have one of the league's elite defensive units, fantasy managers should continue to fire up the Jets D/ST with confidence in all formats.
news.title: Jets D/ST - Week 2 Outlook for Fantasy Football

news.contents: Kelley appears likely to get the bulk of the work out of the Chargers backfield in Sunday's game against the Titans with Austin Ekeler (ankle) listed as doubtful for the contest, Noah Camras of SI.com reports.
news.analysis: The Chargers leaned heavily on their ground attack in a 36-34 loss to the Dolphins in Week 1, allowing both Ekeler (16 carries for 117 yards and a touchdown, four catches for 47 yards on five targets) and Kelley (16 carries for 91 yards and a touchdown, no catches on one target) to come through with useful stat lines. Unless Ekeler -- who didn't practice all week -- makes more progress in his recovery from the ankle injury than anticipated as Sunday's 1 p.m. ET kickoff approaches, he'll be inactive for Week 2, clearing the way for Kelley to take on a major role in one of the NFL's better offenses. Even if the Chargers rely more heavily on the passing game than they did in Week 1, Kelley should still operate as the clear-cut top option on the ground while also seeing more involvement than usual as a receiver. The other two healthy running backs on the Chargers' 53-man roster -- Elijah Dotson and Isaiah Spiller -- have combined for 54 career offensive snaps, and neither may be trusted to handle any sort of meaningful change-of-pace role behind Kelley.
news.title: Looks primed for lead role Week 2

news.contents: Johnson (hamstring) has been ruled out ahead of Monday's game against the Browns, Mike DeFabo of The Athletic reports.
news.analysis: This shouldn't come as a surprise to fantasy managers given Johnson's injury suffered in Week 1 was thought to cause a multi-week absence. In the veteran's absence, expect Calvin Austin and Allen Robinson to split opportunities in the slot opposite outside stalwart George Pickens.
news.title: Unsurprisingly ruled out

news.contents: Pittsburgh Steelers wide receiver Diontae Johnson (hamstring) missed practice for the second straight day this week on Friday and isn't expected to play on Monday night in Week 2 against the Cleveland Browns after injuring his hamstring in the Week 1 loss to the San Francisco 49ers. With Johnson potentially out for up to a month, second-year wideout Calvin Austin III is expected to see more playing time and will start in three-wide sets next to George Pickens and Allen Robinson II.
